    group: {people: "Pohnpeian", language: "Pohnpeian", location: "Pohnpei, FSM"},
    info: [
      `Luk-of-Heaven was a Uone man. Reportedly he was a master speaker who knew all the stories of olden times. When he became an old man he got sick, worsened, and died. Now when he had closed his eyes in death, those beside him did not decide to bury his body quickly.`,
      `When he had died and was lying on his mat, his body was lying there but his spirit was going about everywhere, reportedly walking on the seas and under the seas and going to the lands abroad and the lands nearby, until finally his spiritual voyage was finished, and his spirit returned again into his body, and he came to life again.`,
      `He then composed a song, supposedly a song about his spiritual travels around ths earth. And there were many who were astounded at this man’s travels, and also at how he could compose this song after having died and come to life, and was again clever and could fit the words of the song together so that they would go along well. And those who were with him learned the song.`,
      `<b>LUELEN BERNART</b>, born November 28, 1866, was a Pohnpeian nobleman of the Likitan clan (which held the title of Nahnken, prime minister) with strong ties to the ruling families of two of the five kingdoms of Pohnpei. His book, a compilation of the legends, myths, chants, songs, spells, and botanical lore of Pohnpei, was the first written by a Micronesian.`
    ],
    excerpt: [
      `<i>1.</i>`,
      `I just want to die.<br>And go to Mejenian’<br>The place of magic power,<br>so I might come back,<br>And sit as a live person.`,
      `My voice the Underworld<br>Had a cracked sound;<br>A trembling accent.`,
      `I will come back later.<br>And go to Namanair [Southern Harbour],<br>Harbor of Mejenian’,<br>Go to Nami Tipan [Tipan Harbour]<br>And I settled down,<br>And I did not return from<br>Piken Jero [The beach of the Light],<br>At Pikenlenpon’ [The Beach of the Pond of Night]<br>In Japen Jauipon’ [The Land of the Moon];<br>Its light is different;<br>[?] I no longer have my report, lao.`,
      `<sp><i>2.</i>`,
      `The giant Lijarapajet<br>Took me along<br>To Nalipuijet,<br>To visit at her place.`,
      `I was led along.<br>Up into the noble town;<br>But I walked with trembling gait,<br>Walking hanging back.`,
      `Where are you, Lijipuake?<br>come and prepare for me<br>My coconut to hold in my palms,<br>The Paiian Jaunair [Fortune of the Masters of the South].<br>so I may benefit by it<br>In the Naman Paraj<br>The Japueni paik puet<br>The place of creeping spirits, eh.`,
      `White-headed<br>And blind.<br>The Jauparajaj<br>Took up out of<br>Namanijor<br>The dazzle of magic power<br>Was present at Nanimalu<br>At the place of Limalulu<br>And Nalikeneuneu<br>The horned headdress of the left<br>And the horned headdress of the right,<br>So I might sink down and vanish<br>So I might rise up and appear;<br>For I am a full god,<br>I am Jaomenjet<br>So I might have magic power, loa.`,
      `<sp><i>3.</i>`,
      `I wanted to go visit<br>Jakalainpajet [Jokala of the Underworld]<br>At the place of Aujokala<br>And Jauenpajet [Master of the Dance of the Underworld]<br>They two did not want me to go<br>To the Uaunpajet<br>There was a chattering bird there<br>Which stood guard<br>To swallow up<br>Arriving spirits.`,
      `I then came back from<br>Nanpuajaj<br>To the Marain pajet<br>At Nanullap’s place.`,
      `They were finishing a seine<br>At Mejenian’<br>They came and shouted<br>Bearing Kiolap on a litter<br>Where is Jaukiolap<br>He should come and hold in his palms<br>The kava of Puilok<br>And climb with it on board<br>The noble fleet<br>And keep praying, loa.`,
      `<sp><i>4.</i>`,
      `Lienimajajak<br>Should come and bring<br>Medicine of the Underworld.`,
      `Cassytha filiformis<br>Leaves of ualieki la<br>Put it in my face;<br>it should go around me,<br>it should hold me down firmly,<br>My mouth should be open;<br>And my skin was numb<br>My spirit skin,<br>My skin of the seaside, lao.`,
      `<sp><i>5.</i>`,
      `Ijautapa ki<br>In Namanikeip<br>In Namaniuait<br>The place of a true god;<br>One side was black,<br>The other half was spotted;<br>The eijon of Nanjilop<br>Phosphorescent, lao`,
      `<sp><i>6.</i>`,
      `Where is Lieniman’il<br>I should call her hither<br>She should come and apply<br>Her medicine of comforting;<br>The two of them should weep over her<br>So she might return<br>To Nam en Nanjilop<br>Auni Mejenian’, eh,<br>Set a place for me with<br>Fanned me with<br>A bunch of red Cordyline;<br>That I might turn to the left,<br>That I might turn to the right,<br>Spinning aobut, lao.<br>. . .`
    ],
